Zero Order kinetics -  clearance of drugs that {{c1::is the same}} for given time interval.  E.g., {{c1::alcohol}}, aspirin and {{c1::phenytoin}}
Half-life (t1/2) - time it takes for a drug to reach {{c1::50%}} of it’s original (or previous) concentration in the body.
Clearance (CL) - The volume which the body {{c1::eliminates}} of drug from its system per unit time. Generally eliminated by {{c1::kidneys}}, but may include saliva, sweat, and bile.

Steady-state concentration (Css)- the point at which a drug reaches the desired drug plasma concentration (generally within the Therapeutic window). Usually requires {{c1::4 or 5}} repeated doses of a drug administered at its half-life to get to {{c1::97-100}}% of pharmacological steady state assuming first order kinetics.

Therapeutic window - the range between {{c1::Minimal Toxic Concentration}} (MEC Toxic) and {{c1::Minimal Effective Concentration}} (MEC therapeutic). This is the window in which the drug has the {{c1::desired}} effect without {{c1::adverse side effects}}.

Discuss drug metabolism/biotransformation.

Drugs can be delivered as drugs or {{c1::pro-drugs}}.  Eventually the drugs are metabolized by the {{c1::liver}}.  If a drug is delivered as a pro-drug, it will need to first be {{c1::metabolized}} in order to act.  However, a drug in its active form that is metabolized by the liver will become {{c1::inactivated}}.  Example a patient on warfarin that is then given {{c1::erythromycin}} may experience bleeding, because, {{c1::erythromycin}} deactivates the liver enzyme {{c1::CY P450}} in the liver that metabolizes warfarin. Conversely, a patient on warfarin may experience an ischemic episode if the patient receives the drug {{c1::phenytoin}}, because, {{c1::phenytoin}} increases the activity of P450 and thus deactivates more warfarin.
